                    "reference_content": "Data Structures and Algorithms (DSA) are fundamental to computer science. They provide a systematic way to organize and manage data for efficient access and modification.  This course will guide you through essential DSA concepts using C++. First, you need to set up your environment.  You can use an IDE like Visual Studio Code with the C++ extension, or an online compiler like Repl.it or C++ Shell. To write a basic C++ program, create a file named `main.cpp`.  Include the `<iostream>` library for input/output operations.  Here's a simple \"Hello, World!\" program:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nint main() {\n    std::cout << \"Hello, World!\" << std::endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nTo compile this, use a C++ compiler (like g++): `g++ main.cpp -o main`.  Then, run it: `./main`. C++ introduces several data types like `int` (integers), `float` (floating-point numbers), `double` (double-precision floating-point numbers), `char` (characters), and `bool` (boolean values - `true` or `false`). Variables are declared using `type variable_name;` (e.g., `int age;`). Input is read using `std::cin >> variable_name;`, and output is displayed using `std::cout << variable_name << std::endl;`. Understanding these basics is vital before diving deeper into DSA.",
