                    "reference_content": "Arrays are contiguous blocks of memory that store elements of the same data type. They are declared as `type array_name[size];` (e.g., `int numbers[5];`). Arrays have a fixed size determined at compile time. Vectors, part of the C++ Standard Template Library (STL), provide dynamic arrays that can resize themselves automatically. To use vectors, include the `<vector>` header. Vectors are declared as `std::vector<type> vector_name;` (e.g., `std::vector<int> numbers;`). Basic operations include `push_back(element)` to add elements at the end, `size()` to get the number of elements, `at(index)` or `[index]` to access elements, and `pop_back()` to remove the last element. Vectors can be initialized with a specific size and initial value: `std::vector<int> vec(10, 0);` creates a vector of 10 integers, all initialized to 0. For example:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\n\nint main() {\n    std::vector<int> numbers;\n    numbers.push_back(10);\n    numbers.push_back(20);\n    std::cout << \"Size: \" << numbers.size() << std::endl;  // Output: 2\n    std::cout << \"Element at index 0: \" << numbers << std::endl; // Output: 10\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nUnderstanding the difference between arrays and vectors, and when to use each, is crucial for efficient DSA implementation.",
