                    "reference_content": "Pointers are variables that store the memory address of another variable. They are declared as `type *pointer_name;` (e.g., `int *ptr;`). Dynamic memory allocation allows you to allocate memory during runtime. The `new` keyword is used to allocate memory on the heap, and `delete` is used to free the allocated memory.  Failing to `delete` allocated memory leads to memory leaks.  For arrays, use `delete[]`. Example:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nint main() {\n    int *ptr = new int;  // Allocate memory for an integer\n    *ptr = 10;\n    std::cout << \"Value: \" << *ptr << std::endl;  // Output: 10\n    delete ptr;  // Free the allocated memory\n\n    int *arr = new int;  // Allocate memory for an array of 5 integers\n    for (int i = 0; i < 5; ++i) {\n        arr[i] = i * 2;\n    }\n    delete[] arr;  // Free the allocated memory for the array\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nAlways remember to `delete` what you `new` to avoid memory leaks. Pointers are crucial for creating dynamic data structures like linked lists and trees.",
