                    "reference_content": "A linked list is a linear data structure where elements are stored in nodes. Each node contains data and a pointer to the next node in the sequence. The last node's pointer points to `nullptr`. A singly linked list has nodes with a pointer to the next node only. Implementing a linked list involves creating a `Node` struct/class and a `LinkedList` class. The `Node` class typically contains the data and a pointer to the next node:\n\n```cpp\nstruct Node {\n    int data;\n    Node* next;\n};\n```\n\nInsertion can be done at the beginning, end, or middle of the list. Deletion involves removing a node from the list and updating the pointers of adjacent nodes. Here's an example of inserting at the beginning:\n\n```cpp\nvoid insertAtBeginning(Node** head, int newData) {\n    Node* newNode = new Node();\n    newNode->data = newData;\n    newNode->next = *head;\n    *head = newNode;\n}\n```\n\nSimilarly, deletion involves finding the node to be deleted and updating the `next` pointer of the previous node. Linked lists are useful for dynamic data storage where the size is not known beforehand.",
